  "sourceCode": "Employer Portal",
  "title": "Marine Service Engineer (NavCom)",
  "description": "<ul>\n  <li>Marine radar systems, chartplotters, ECDIS, AIS, VDR, VHF radios, MF/HF SSB, autopilots, maritime IT equipment, and VSAT systems are just a few of the marine navigation and communication systems that need to be installed, troubleshooted, and maintained.  </li>\n  <li>To guarantee optimum performance and adherence to safety rules, perform routine maintenance checks and inspections on installed systems.  </li>\n  <li>Effectively identify and fix technical problems to reduce downtime and guarantee that onboard systems continue to function.  </li>\n  <li>Assist crew members on board with technical support and direction for the upkeep and operation of navigation and communication systems.  </li>\n  <li>When necessary, organise installations, upgrades, and repairs with internal teams and external stakeholders.  </li>\n  <li>Stay up to date on changes in the maritime navigation and communication systems sector, laws, and technology.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Requirements:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>A bachelor's degree in telecommunications, electrical/electronics engineering, or a similar discipline.  </li>\n  <li>Four years or more of practical expertise installing, debugging, and maintaining marine communication and navigation systems. </li>\n  <li>Solid understanding of networking and IT concepts and procedures.  </li>\n  <li>It is advised to have a General Operator's Certificate (GOC).  </li>\n  <li>It is preferable to have knowledge of marine electrical and electronic systems.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><br></p>",
